{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522123"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:41:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:41:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13801"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13801"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.11,0.04,0.02,0.8]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6418"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53636"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6418"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13801"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39096"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1598"},{"type":"tags","id":"3357"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12640"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14026"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53636"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department following two weeks of progressive malaise, increasing abdominal distension and jaundice. He has no significant medical or surgical history and does not take any regular medications. He is a non-smoker and drinks two standard drinks of alcohol a week. He has a family history of antiphospholipid syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with vital signs within normal limits. His clinical examination reveals an abnormality of the abdominal skin (Image). His blood tests revealed abnormalities in liver function tests with bilirubin 60 \u00b5mol/L (2\u201324), ALT 340 U/L (\u0026lt;55), AST 440 U/L (\u0026lt;45). An ultrasound abdomen revealed reversed flow in the hepatic veins.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis for this man\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Biliary atresia","Fitz-Hugh Curtis syndrome","Haemochromatosis","Choledocholithiasis","Budd-Chiari syndrome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBudd-Chiari syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis in this case. It is characterised by hepatic venous outflow obstruction, typically due to thrombosis of the hepatic veins or inferior vena cava. The patient\u0027s presentation with progressive malaise, abdominal distension, and jaundice is consistent with this diagnosis. The key diagnostic feature is the reversed flow in hepatic veins on ultrasound. Additionally, the family history of antiphospholipid syndrome is significant, as this condition predisposes to thrombosis and is a known risk factor for Budd-Chiari syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiliary atresia\u003C/strong\u003E is a congenital condition affecting newborns and infants, not adults. It causes bile duct obstruction leading to cholestasis and jaundice but would not explain the reversed hepatic venous flow or the acute onset in an adult.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFitz-Hugh Curtis syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a complication of pelvic inflammatory disease, causing inflammation of the liver capsule. While it can cause right upper quadrant pain, it does not typically cause jaundice or reversed hepatic venous flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemochromatosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a disorder of iron metabolism leading to iron overload in various organs, including the liver. While it can cause liver dysfunction, it typically has a more insidious onset and would not explain the acute presentation or the reversed hepatic venous flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholedocholithiasis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the presence of gallstones in the common bile duct. While it can cause jaundice and abnormal liver function tests, it would not explain the reversed hepatic venous flow or the abdominal distension seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, the combination of clinical presentation, family history, and ultrasound findings strongly points towards Budd-Chiari syndrome as the most likely diagnosis. The next steps in management would include further imaging (such as CT or MRI) to confirm the diagnosis and assess the extent of venous thrombosis, as well as initiating anticoagulation therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Budd-Chiari syndrome is characterised by hepatic venous outflow obstruction, often presenting with abdominal distension, jaundice, and abnormal liver function tests.","Reversed flow in hepatic veins on ultrasound is a key diagnostic feature of Budd-Chiari syndrome.","Antiphospholipid syndrome is a risk factor for Budd-Chiari syndrome due to its prothrombotic nature."],"references":["Hitawala AA, Gupta V. Budd-Chiari Syndrome. In: StatPearls [Online]. [Updated 2023 Jan 30]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK558941/","Gaillard F, Sharma R, Lazic S, et al. Budd-Chiari syndrome. In: Radiopaedia.org. Accessed 2024 Aug 19. Available at: https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-1023"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39096"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13801"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type"